<section xml:id="optimization-using-quadratic-functions">
  <title>Optimization Using Quadratic Functions</title>
<introduction>
  <p>
    <term>Optimization</term> is an area of mathematics specializing in finding the absolute extrema of an equation to solve a real-world problem. Quadratic functions give a solid introduction to the topic with many mathematical and real-world applications.
  </p>
</introduction>
  <subsection xml:id="applications-to-geometry">
    <title>Applications to Geometry</title>
    <example xml:id="minimizing-distance-to-parabola">
      <title>Minimizing the Distance from a Point to a Parabola</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the minimum distance between the parabola <m>y = x^2</m> and the point <m>(0, 3)</m>.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <caption>The point <m>(0,3)</m> with multiple line segments connecting to different points of the the parabola <m>y=x^2</m>. One of the points is labeled as the closest point.</caption>
          <image source="placeholder-point-to-parabola.png" decorative="yes"/>
        </figure>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          The minimum distance is <m>\frac{\sqrt{11}}{2}</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Let <m>(x, x^2)</m> be a point on the parabola. The distance between this point and <m>(0, 3)</m> is given by
          <me>D = \sqrt{(x - 0)^2 + (x^2 - 3)^2}.</me>
          Since distance is always positive, minimizing <m>D</m> is equivalent to minimizing <m>D^2.</m> 
          Therefore, we need to minimize <me>D^2 = (x-0)^2 + (x^2 - 3)^2.</me> Simplifying the equation, we get
          <md>
            <mrow>D^2\amp= (x-0)^2 + (x^2 - 3)^2 \\</mrow>
            <mrow>D^2\amp= x^2 + (x^4 - 6x^2 + 9) \\</mrow>
            <mrow>D^2\amp= x^4 - 5x^2 + 9</mrow> 
          </md>  
          Notice that this equation is quadratic in form. Let <m>u = x^2</m> and <m>u^2=(x^2)^2=x^4</m>. 
          This implies that <me>D^2 = u^2 - 5u + 9.</me>
          Since this is a quadratic function with <m>a &gt;0</m>, we know that the vertex is both a local and absolute minimum.
          Therefore, the value of <m>k</m> is the minimum value of <m>D^2</m>.
          First, we have to find the value of <m>h</m>:
          <md>
            <mrow>h\amp= -\frac{b}{2a} \\</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= -\frac{-5}{2(1)} \\</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= \frac{5}{2}</mrow>
          </md>
          Now, we let <m>u = h=\frac{5}{2}</m> and substitute into the equation for <m>D^2</m> to find the value of <m>k</m>:
          <md>
            <mrow>k\amp= \left(\frac{5}{2}\right)^2 - 5\left(\frac{5}{2}\right) + 9 \\</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= \frac{25}{4} - \frac{50}{4} + \frac{36}{4} \\</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= \frac{11}{4}\\</mrow>
          </md>
          Thus, the minimum value of <m>D^2</m> is <m>\frac{11}{4}</m>, and the minimum distance is 
          <md>
            <mrow>D\amp= \sqrt{D^2} \\</mrow>
            <mrow>D\amp= \sqrt{\frac{11}{4}} \\</mrow>
            <mrow>D\amp= \frac{\sqrt{11}}{\sqrt{4}} \\</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= \frac{\sqrt{11}}{2}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>


    </example>
  </subsection>




