  <!-- Subsection: Applications from Physics -->
  <!-- =========================================================== -->
  <subsection xml:id="applications-from-physics">
    <title>Applications from Physics</title>

    <theorem xml:id="height-of-projectiles">
      <title>Height of Projectiles</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The height of a projectile (in feet, ignoring air resistance) is given by the equation
          <me>h(t) = -16t^2 + v_0t + h_0,</me>
          where <m>v_0</m> is the initial velocity (in feet per second) and <m>h_0</m> is the initial height (in feet).
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>


    <example xml:id="maximum-height-of-projectile">
      <title>Finding the Maximum Height of a Projectile</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A soccer ball is kicked upward with an initial velocity of <m>40</m> ft/s from a height of <m>3</m> feet.  
          Its height after <m>t</m> seconds is given by <m>h(t) = -16t^2 + 40t + 3.</m>  
          Find the time when the ball reaches its maximum height and determine that height.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <caption>The trajectory of the soccer ball showing the maximum height point.</caption>
          <image source="placeholder-projectile-trajectory.png">
            <shortdescription>Parabolic path of a soccer ball reaching a peak before descending.</shortdescription>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          The ball reaches a maximum height of <m>28</m> feet after <m>1.25</m> seconds.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The height function <m>h(t) = -16t^2 + 40t + 3</m> is a downward-opening parabola.  
          The time of the maximum height occurs at the vertex, given by
          <md>
            <mrow>t\amp= -\frac{b}{2a} \\</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= -\frac{40}{2(-16)} \\</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= 1.25 \text{ seconds.}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          Substitute <m>t = 1.25</m> into the height equation to find the maximum height:
          <md>
            <mrow>h(1.25)\amp= -16(1.25)^2 + 40(1.25) + 3 \\</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= -16(1.5625) + 50 + 3 \\</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= -25 + 50 + 3 \\</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= 28 \text{ feet.}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>

    </example>


    <example xml:id="finding-initial-velocity-from-max-height">
      <title>Finding Initial Height and Velocity from Maximum Height</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose a rocket reaches a maximal height of <m>700</m> feet, <m>5</m> seconds after launch.  
          Find its initial velocity and initial height.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          The rocket was launched from a height of <m>300</m> feet with an initial velocity of <m>160</m> ft/s.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Since the maximal height occurs at the vertex of the height equation <m>h(t) = -16t^2 + v_0t + h_0</m>, we know that the vertex is at the point <m>(5,700)</m>.
          In the height function, notice that <m>b=v_0</m>. Since we know the values of <m>t</m> and <m>a</m>, we can solve for <m>v_0</m> using the formula <m>t=\frac{-b}{2a}.</m>
          Plugging these values in, the following calculations shows us how to find <m>v_0</m>:
          <md>
            <mrow>5\amp= -\frac{v_0}{2(-16)} \\</mrow>
            <mrow>5\amp= \frac{v_0}{32} \\</mrow>
            <mrow>v_0\amp= 5(32) \\</mrow>
            <mrow>v_0\amp= 160 \text{ ft/s.}</mrow>
          </md>
          Now that we know the initial velocity, we can substitute <m>t=5</m>, <m>v_0=160</m>, and <m>h(t)=700</m> into the height equation to find the initial height <m>h_0</m>
          The following calculation shows us how do to this:
          <md>
            <mrow>700\amp= -16(5)^2 + 160(5) + h_0 \\</mrow>
            <mrow>700\amp- -16(25) + 800 + h_0 \\</mrow>
            <mrow>700\amp= -400 + 800 + h_0 \\</mrow>
            <mrow>700\amp= 400 + h_0 \\</mrow>
            <mrow>h_0\amp= 700 - 400 \\</mrow>
            <mrow>h_0\amp= 300 \text{ feet.}</mrow> 
          </md>
          Therefore, the equation of the height function is <me>h(t) = -16t^2 + 160t + 300.</me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>




