  <subsection xml:id="applications-from-economics">
    <title>Applications from Economics</title>

    <example xml:id="maximizing-profit-in-game-design">
      <title>Maximizing Revenue in Game Design</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A mobile game sells for <m>\$1.00</m> and attracts <m>50{,}000</m> downloads.  
          For every <m>\$0.10</m> increase in price, downloads decrease by <m>2{,}000</m>.  
          Find the maximum revenue, the price that maximizes revenue, and the number of downloads at that price.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          The price that maximizes revenue is <m>\$1.75</m>, yielding approximately <m>35{,}000</m> downloads. The maximum revenue is <m>\$61{,}250.</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Let <m>x</m> represent the number of <m>\$0.10</m> increases.  
          Then the price is <m>p = 1 + 0.1x</m>, and the number of downloads is <m>n = 50{,}000 - 2{,}000x</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          The revenue <m>R</m> is the price of the video game times the number of downloads. Converting that into symbols and simplifying, we get the following calculation:
          <md>
            <mrow>R\amp= p \times n \\</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= (1 + 0.1x)(50{,}000 - 2{,}000x) \\</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= 50{,}000 + 5{,}000x - 2{,}000x - 200x^2 \\</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= -200x^2 + 3{,}000x + 50{,}000</mrow>
          </md>
        Since the value of <m>a</m> is negative, the parabola opens downward, and the <m>R</m>-coordinate of the vertex is the maximum profit.
        To find the value of <m>R</m> at the vertex, we first find the value of <m>x</m> at the vertex using the formula <m>x = \frac{-b}{2a}.</m> The following calculation shows how to do this:
        <md>
          <mrow>x\amp= \frac{-b}{2a} \\</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp= \frac{-3{,}000}{2(-200)} \\</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp= 7.5</mrow>
        </md>
        Now, we substitute <m>x = 7.5</m> into the revenue equation to find the maximum revenue:
        <md>
          <mrow>R(7.5)\amp= -200(7.5)^2 + 3{,}000(7.5) + 50{,}000 \\</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp= -200(56.25) + 22{,}500 + 50{,}000 \\</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp= -11{,}250 + 22{,}500 + 50{,}000 \\</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp= 61{,}250</mrow>
        </md>
        Thus, the maximum revenue is <m>\$61{,}250</m>, which occurs when <m>x = 7.5.</m>. To find the price that maximizes revenue, we substitute <m>x = 7.5</m> into the price equation:
        <md>
          <mrow>p\amp= 1 + 0.1(7.5) \\</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp= 1 + 0.75 \\</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp= 1.75</mrow>
        </md>
        Therefore, the price that maximizes revenue is <m>\$1.75</m>. To find the number of downloads, we perform the following calculation:
      <md>
        <mrow>n\amp= 50{,}000 - 2{,}000(7.5) \\</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 50{,}000 - 15{,}000 \\</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 35{,}000</mrow>
      </md>
        Therefore, the number of downloads at that price is approximately <m>35{,}000.</m>
      </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
